host_about:
Im a Mexican who loves to travel so decided to rent out my home while im not around. I love Airbnb since its the perfect way to travel and to receive like minded guests. I have prepared a full on home & City Guide with my personal recommendations for food, art galleries, sites, museums & parks this way you will be able to experience Mexico city as a local and not fall into the tourist traps. 
Feel free to let me know what the purpose of your visit is and if you need some extra tips :) 

Please treat my home like you would your own :)

*If you want to know more about the house I was interviewed for a interior design magazine to talk about my home  the title of the publication is "Blending Modern with Vintage in This Stunning Mexico City  Home" you can find it on the internet. Below the full article:

BLENDING MODERN WITH VINTAGE IN THIS STUNNING MEXICO CITY HOME

Located in Mexico city’s stylish San Miguel Chapultepec neighborhood, Santiago Vertiz first moved into his 2006-built home ten years ago.

At the time, Santiago didn’t own furniture and slept on a mattress in the empty space – an image in stark contrast to the harmonious blend of modern vs vintage we now see. Vertiz spent years searching for pieces that inspire him, whilst highlighting his Mexican culture.
Fascinated by pre-Columbian cultures and inspired by childhood memories of his grandparents’ houses, many antique pieces fill the house, as well as colourful original modern art, handicrafts and textiles from Mexico and Guatemala.

Nature plays an important role throughout the home, and an entire wall of glass doors opens to the patio, seamlessly blending the indoors with the outdoors. Says Vertiz, “Plants play a very important role in life and in my home. They are the protagonists that bring life, change, and color.”
Santiago’s mission has been to recover, collect, restore, and redesign furniture and other pieces that inspire him, while working with the house’s unique architectural features to amplify its height and to bring life to the space.

What attracted you to your home?
Mexico City can be very hectic, you can easily spend half of your life in traffic. I felt it was a luxury to be able to walk to places without using a car.
I knew I wanted to live in a central location, close to the classic neighborhoods – Condesa, Roma and Polanco are some of the most well-known, but also in high demand. A friend introduced me to San Miguel Chapultepec, which is a residential neighborhood making it quiet, safe and strategically located. It’s across the street from Bosque de Chapultepec and home to many artists and galleries.
Secondly, I was excited by the architectural project. The architect’s goal was to make a town house project resembling a loft, instead of a classical building. There are actually ten identical houses with spacious, double-height ceilings overlooking a private terrace.
When I discovered the space, it had already been built, but I was able to modify the size of the terrace space, and since the view is very important to me, we made a front wall to allow plants to grow in.

Did you have a vision for your home?
I wanted my house to be a place I felt comfortable in, that I could enjoy and feel relaxed. I didn’t want to have a party house – as I said to an old roommate, “My house is my temple”.
I had to improvise and play around a lot with the location of certain pieces, so there was trial and error involved. I would stay up at night thinking of new things I could do to the house – it was a lot of fun!

How did your fascination with pre-Columbian cultures influence the design of your home?
My maternal grandparents came from Merida, Yucatan and had deep knowledge of Mayan cultures. My grandfather would tell us tales of his many visits into the jungle and his friendship with archeologist Alberto Ruz Lhuillier. Not only was he present in the discovery of the Pakal tomb, but he actually helped by providing some of the machinery needed to uncover the tomb. My oldest uncle, a boy at the time, took the first pictures ever of the tomb. I’ve inherited a deep admiration and respect for the Mayas and their communities.
One spring break my parents took us on a road trip, passing through Veracruz into Chiapas, and visiting different ruins along the way. We camped out in the middle of the jungle, next to the Usumacinta river on the border of Mexico and Guatemala. We walked some distance to the ruins of Yaxichilan, and in another location camped with a Lacandon Community, reliving the experience that my grandfather once had.
When I visit a region, anywhere in the world, I value the natives’ culture and appreciate the hard work and beauty that goes into their handcrafts.

I love art, history and social media!!!

host_about:
Hola, soy Damián, artista y escritor, mexicano de nacimiento. Estoy a favor de la igualdad, los derechos humanos y los gobiernos progresistas.
---
UN HOSPEDAJE MÁS RESPONSABLE
He buscado no crear una simple casa de huéspedes, sino también un territorio intercultural, neutral y de intercambio saberes. Un espacio que busca proveer de una estancia tranquila y agradable dentro de una ciudad y una sociedad globalizada que cada vez se gentrifica y homogeniza más, que se extiende sin llevar a cabo la labor de resolver las grandes problemáticas de los espacios urbanos y que requiere dar una solución. 

PD. Te informo que con tu reserva, parte de las ganancias se destinan al apoyo de migrantes y artistas locales. :)

neiborhood_overview:
La colonia Roma forma parte del corazón de la CDMX y ha quedado grabada en el imaginario de las y los mexicanos porque sus construcciones y su diseño han sido plasmados en algunas obras de literatura y en diversas películas mexicanas. De acuerdo con el Instituto de Investigaciones Sociales de la UNAM, su estilo resalta principalmente por “su arquitectura art decó, art nouveau y neogótico, situación que da una sensación de haberse detenido en el tiempo”. Fue fundada a principios del siglo XX por los empresarios Edward Walter Orrin, Pedro Lascuráin y Cassius Lamm. Se le dio el nombre de “Roma” debido a que antes el terreno era conocido como los Potreros de Romita.

Desde el principio -al igual que la Condesa- se convirtió en una zona exclusiva de las clases altas, por tal motivo, se empezaron a edificar lujosas casas y hasta mansiones. De hecho, desde su planeación se consideró que debía ser un lugar de “ensueño” parecido a las colonias europeas, esa fue la razón por la que se

Quiet traditional mexican neighborhood with lots of small and local restaurants, close to at least 3 universities, close to the City’s public transport system. With a large mall within walking distance and at least 4 more within a 20 min drive. description:
Experience the perfect combination of colonial charm and modern comfort in our cozy home. Located in a safe and exclusive neighborhood, you'll find peace in this quiet haven. Immerse yourself in Mexican culture while being just a stone's throw away from the city's most upscale shopping mall and hospital. Our familiar atmosphere is sure to make you feel right at home. Explore the rich cultural and historic sites such as San Angel or experience the modern vibe of the nearby Santa Fe neighborhood.

The space
Welcome to our spacious and comfortable home! Our property has three bedrooms, each with a cozy bed and plenty of closet space to store your belongings during your stay. There are also 3.5 bathrooms, so you won't have to wait in line to freshen up in the morning.

neiborhood_overview:
Our home is in San Jerónimo Lidice, which is one of the most beautiful colonial towns inside Mexico City and with one of the most beautiful churches. It is simply a magnificent place to visit. Most residents refer to the area simply as "San Jeronimo." The Church was built by the Franciscan order in the 16th century and its main celebration takes place on September 30.

Its peculiar name is in honor of the Czechoslovakian village Lídice, razed by the Germans in 1942. This colony, located to the south west of Mexico City, has become an attractive place to reside due to its proximity to Ciudad Universitaria, as well as other main landmarks of the city such as Coyoacan, San Angel, Tlalpan. It is around 30 minutes driving to Polanco, Condesa and Roma. And around 45 minutes driving to Mexico City Downtown.

The space
The house has a total of eight bedrooms. Two bedrooms are on the first floor of the house. Six bedrooms are on the second floor of the house. Six bedrooms have two double beds each. One bedroo has one double bed. Only one bedroom has a king size bed.
The house has four full bathrooms.

name: Hermosa Casona Porfiriana
description:
Esta casona data del año de 1895 aproximadamente, restaurada en su totalidad hace a penas algunos años, es una de las joyas más hermosas de la colonia Santa María La Ribera.

The space
Esta es una casa grande con 2 recámaras bastante cómodas. La primer recámara tiene dos cámas y la segunda solo una cama queen size. La sala y el comedor se encuentran en el mismo salón y están comunicados con la cocina que es muy amplia y espaciosa. En general la casa tiene mucha luz natural durante el día. Cuenta con dos baños, dos regaderas y dos lavabos dentro del mismo gran baño de la casa.

Guest access
La casa está en un terreno muy grande el cual cuenta con un patio que se comparte con otros 6 departamentos que están atrás de la propiedad. Hay un sótano al que no se permite el acceso.
host_about: Casar restaurada y decorada con una colección de arte moderno, muebles de época.  Areas de contemplación, lectura y recreación.

neiborhood_overview:
La Roma, or Colonia Roma, is a dynamic neighborhood with a rich cultural variety and an animated vibe. It offers something for everyone, from gourmet food and cultural institutions to parks and nightlife, making it a must-see destination for anyone traveling to Mexico City.

One of the main attractions of La Roma is the Mercado Roma, a gourmet market that offers a wide variety of Mexican and international cuisine, as well as artisan products and designer clothes. The market is a popular destination for foodies and locals alike.

In the gastronomic aspect, after a 5-minute walk you will find the famous Rosetta restaurant, where you can try delicious food and enjoy a warm and modern atmosphere.

Roma is also known for its extensive nightlife, with a variety of bars, clubs and music venues catering to different tastes. Just a 10-minute walk away you will find SUPRA ROOFTOP, a terrace bar where you can go out for a few drinks and have a great time.

If you peek your head behind some of the foreboding doors on San Miguel’s tree-lined streets, you’ll find art galleries, creative food and stately homes. Next door to one of the biggest city parks in the world, it makes for a perfect detour from the typical tourist itinerary.

name: Casa Uh-May: Huge house w/ private rooftop
description:
Casa Uh-May takes its name from a mayan town in Quintana Roo where the artisans handcrafted most of its decoration.
Beautifully decorated with 7 bedrooms, private rooftop, a patio, and private parking, you'll feel in an oasis of peace, but steps away from everything you want to enjoy in Mexico City.

The space
The layout of this house is like no other, which makes part of it's magic but it's also important for you to understand.
Ground floor: first you have the garage adjacent to the patio, the enter to the house and you'll find a king size bedroom, living room, dining room, half bathroom (toilet) and the kitchen.
Floor 1: 3 king size bedrooms, the main bathroom, and outside you'll fin the laundry and an outdoor shower.
To go to the top floor you'll find 3 ways, a door in the hall next to the main bathroom, the black stairs in the middle room (perfect for when it's raining), a door in the first room where you can find the laundry too.
Top

name: Nueva Casa Rosa en el corazón de la colonia Roma
description:
Una hermosa y - recién remodelada - casa rosada en el corazón de la colonia Roma.

Un hogar fuera de casa para pasar unos días o una temporada larga cerca de sitios históricos, tiendas y restaurantes locales en un barrio con actitud.

Todas las comodidades en una casa con personalidad y una arquitectura e interiorismo impecables.

Other things to note
Bienvenidos a Pink Tiny House, a home for artists and creatives looking for a bohemian experience of Mexico City.

We are located in the heart of Roma Norte—a neighborhood teeming with music, art, bars, restaurants and cafes—and just a short walk from Parque México, Parque España, Cibeles Fountain, Bosque de Chapultepec and plenty of public transport options.

A house with strong character but filled with warm details to make you feel at home.

name: Entire Home en Vecindad Murales
description:
A completely remodeled 100 year old home in a Traditional Vecindad with Secret Murals made from local Latin Muralists.

The house is a three story home with three rooms ... a bedroom with a full bed, an art room with a sofa-bed and an office.

The idea of the home is to one day make it into an Artistic Residence in order to promote art and culture in Mexico City.

Great COYOACAN location ... Metro - 10 minute walk, Center of Coyoacan - 15 minute walk & many markets and parks nearby.

The space
The home is the perfect retreat for a couple looking to get a genuine Coyoacan experience. You will have the privacy of your own home with an art studio and an office but still feel you have a loving neighborhood where you will be able to meet and hang out with neighbors in the common space of the vecindad (courtyard)
host_about:
Fun loving half gringo half mexican! Born in Mexico, raised in the states, and now living and loving Mexico City for 13 years. Formal Cultural Professor at Penn State University ... know all the best secrets of Mexico City.

Currently run a social business called Isla Urbana that helps low income families and communities with water scarcity issues with rainwater harvesting systems.  Check it out … maybe you can volunteer for us!

Currently live with the two dogs and a cat in a 3 bedroom townhouse close to Coyoacan which I rent two beautiful loft bedrooms and at times the entire house.

Very passionate plant and sustainability lover!!

neiborhood_overview: Discover the vibrant Condesa neighborhood in Mexico City! Known for its lively atmosphere, trendy bars and restaurants, and beautiful parks, Condesa is a must-visit destination for any traveler. Stroll down the tree-lined streets and admire the Art Deco architecture, or spend an afternoon relaxing in one of the many parks, such as Parque Mexico or Parque España. At night, experience the neighborhood's lively nightlife scene, with an abundance of bars, clubs, and music venues to choose from. Whether you're a foodie, art lover, or just looking for a good time, Condesa has something for everyone. Book your stay in Condesa now and experience one of the most exciting neighborhoods in Mexico City!
